snippet.textDisplay: Nice guy he may be but there is no way Deontay brought Fury into Big Time. In fact, it was the other way round. Fury had fought Vladimir Klitschko and beat him. The WBC honored Vitaly Klitschko by naming him WBC champion in perpetuity after he retired.. Wilder was gifted with that vacated belt. He never earned it. Wilder had not fought anyone of any standing in all his fights, certainly no champion. Except for an aging Luis Ortiz who had a heart disorder for which he took medication. Wilder fought dead men.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm no boxing expert but after watching the replay of the first fight, although I thought Fury was winning just like most of everyone else, but I accepted the draw decision. If Fury would have been knocked down once instead of twice, I still would have given the decision to Fury. But by a split decision.  If he got knocked down twice, which he did (and almost out because of the controversy counting) I could see the end result as a draw. The later rounds of a championship fight is especially big. And the challenger to me, has to be convincing trying to take out the champ especially via KO which Fury failed to do. If wilder would have knocked down Fury for the third time in that fight, I would have given the decision to Wilder. After getting knocked down three times in a fight kinda tells you something. But then again I've seen fighters get up from the canvas after being knocked down multiple times to  KO their opponents. Besides from the obvious KOs I think your own  best instincts, you decide with your own eyes who won the fight is most important.
